  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Burbank sits on the eastern edge of the Brisbane City Council area, between Chandler to the north and the bushland reserves that follow Bulimba Creek to the south and west. It is one of the tightest acreage suburbs inside the city boundary, with most holdings sitting on lifestyle-scale blocks rather than standard residential allotments. Many of those blocks have been held by the same families for decades, and turnover in any given year is low. That tightness shapes the seller's market in ways that buyers from outside the suburb often underestimate.</p>

      <p>The internal character of Burbank is more varied than the price ranges from outside suggest. There are blocks with cleared useable paddocks suited to horses or hobby-farm use, blocks with significant bushland or creek frontage that present as private bush retreats, and blocks closer to the Old Cleveland Road corridor that read as larger residential rather than true acreage. Each of those character types attracts a different buyer profile, and the campaign for a Burbank property needs to recognise which segment it sits in.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Who is buying in Burbank</h2>
      <p>The dominant buyer in Burbank is the lifestyle household that wants genuine acreage inside the Brisbane City Council boundary. These buyers have typically held a smaller home in Carindale, Chandler, Gumdale or further afield in the eastern suburbs, and are stepping up into a property that offers space, privacy and the ability to keep horses or run a small holding without leaving the city. They are usually in their forties or fifties, often with school-age children or older, and they have done careful homework before they make an offer.</p>

      <p>The equestrian buyer is a meaningful sub-segment in Burbank. Riding access to the surrounding reserves and the suburb's history of horse-friendly holdings means buyers specifically searching for equestrian-suitable properties regularly arrive at Burbank when comparing options across south-east Queensland. Properties with quality fencing, useable cleared paddocks, established stables or shelters, and reasonable hold-down for arena or yard work are positioned to capture that segment, and the campaign material should make those features explicit rather than leave them buried in the property description.</p>

      <p>A third buyer group is the privacy-driven household looking for a bush-retreat character within the city. These buyers are drawn to blocks with substantial bushland frontage, mature trees and visual separation from neighbours rather than to cleared paddock land. The campaign for a property of this kind should lead with the privacy and the outlook, not with land area on its own.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What drives value in Burbank</h2>
      <p>Useable land character is the single biggest value driver. A cleared, level, well-drained block with quality fencing and mains-power services sits in a clearly different price tier to a block of similar gross size that is partly encumbered by easement, drainage issues, or large areas of unusable steep or boggy ground. Buyers in Burbank assess useable land carefully, and the campaign needs to present that useable land honestly rather than rely on headline lot size alone.</p>

      <p>Infrastructure on the block matters more in Burbank than in standard residential suburbs. Quality fencing in good condition, established stables or shelters that comply with current standards, working dams or water systems where present, and properly installed mains-power and sealed driveways all add measurable value. Properties with deferred maintenance on those items will face buyer-driven discount conversations during negotiation, and a pre-campaign audit of those items almost always pays for itself.</p>

      <p>Position relative to the Bulimba Creek reserves and the surrounding bushland is a quieter but real value driver. Blocks that adjoin or look into the reserve system carry a privacy and outlook premium, and that should be reflected in the campaign positioning. Position relative to Old Cleveland Road and the practical commute into Carindale or onto the Gateway Motorway is also a factor for buyers weighing Burbank against more central acreage corridors.</p>

      <p>The standard of the home itself is a significant value contributor at the higher end of the Burbank market. A quality renovated or recently built home on a well-presented block consistently outperforms a tired home on a comparable block, even though the land does the heaviest lifting in a Burbank valuation. Buyers in the modern lifestyle segment expect a home that they can move into rather than a renovation project on top of an acreage commitment.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Preparing your Burbank home for sale</h2>
      <p>Preparation for a Burbank campaign is about the whole holding, not just the house. Fence lines, paddock condition, stable and shed standards, gate hardware, driveway condition, and the general state of any infrastructure on the block are all assessed by serious buyers and will influence both the offer price and the speed at which a buyer commits. A pre-sale walk through the property with clear eyes, identifying every item that a buyer is likely to point to during inspection, is one of the highest-return uses of seller time before a campaign launches.</p>

      <p>For the home itself, the preparation standard is similar to a quality eastern-suburbs residential campaign. Neutral, well-maintained interiors, considered styling that suits the lifestyle positioning of the property, and an outdoor entertaining area that connects the home to the land all support a stronger result. Buyers in Burbank are paying for a lifestyle, and the campaign needs to show them what that lifestyle looks like rather than ask them to imagine it.</p>

      <p>Documentation matters. A clear and accurate plan of the property showing useable land, water infrastructure, easements, and the position of stables or sheds gives serious buyers the confidence to move quickly. A well-prepared contract pack, including current rates, water and any relevant approvals on infrastructure, removes the friction that otherwise extends a Burbank campaign by weeks.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Best time to sell in Burbank</h2>
      <p>Burbank follows the broader Brisbane seasonal pattern, but the effect is less pronounced than in residential suburbs. The strongest windows are autumn (late February through May) and spring (September through November). Autumn tends to produce particularly motivated buyers because lifestyle households researching the move out of standard suburbs through summer arrive in February and March with clear intent and a defined timeline.</p>

      <p>Spring brings more buyers to the market but also more competing acreage listings across south-east Queensland, and an autumn campaign for a Burbank property often runs with cleaner competing-stock conditions. The equestrian buyer is less seasonally driven and more event-driven, so a campaign positioned for that segment can perform well outside the broader peak windows, particularly if the campaign reaches the right specialist audience.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How long does it take to sell in Burbank</h2>
      <p>Well-presented Burbank acreage properties, accurately priced against recent comparable acreage sales rather than against standard residential comparables, typically sell within 40 to 70 days. The lifestyle and equestrian buyer pool is smaller and more specific than a standard residential buyer pool, and the campaign needs the time to reach the right households across south-east Queensland.</p>

      <p>Correct pricing is the single most controllable factor. Overpriced campaigns in Burbank sit longer than they should, attract offers that reflect the extended days on market, and almost always close at a discount that reflects the price-setting error rather than the underlying market. Pricing against the wrong comparable set, particularly against standard residential sales in adjoining suburbs rather than against true acreage sales, is the most common cause of an extended Burbank campaign.</p>

